carl, as a regular on mike's thread, i think i can explain what mike was
talking about - he can clarify when his compaq is up and running again.

mike plays undervalued or overvalued stocks that he expects a decent move out
of over time (of course, the valuation is in his opinion). let's say he feels a
stock s/b properly valued at $20 and it is $12.

he'll buy a 1/3 position so that he has powder dry if it drops lower. if it
goes up immediately then he's happy he''s in. his 1/3 system is designed to
counter the fact that nobody knows what a stock will do short term. it is
designed to minimize risk.

mike's comment about the short term traders is that when they are right they
get a half point or so. when they lose, it may be a couple points. they'll win
more than they lose, but, overall, they'll tend to lose over time.

they look more at trends and stock price noise vs an actual fundamental
analysis of a company.

come on over to the thread. it is the best one on si when mike's computer is up
and running :-)

anyway, i KNOW he'd enjoy your analysis of txn ;-)
