Date:10/8/1997 12:41:00 AM
From:James Clarke

Mike's post deserves more comment. The January effect is very real if you are a
deep value small cap investor. Every December 31 I pick a couple stocks I
already own that are likely to go up in January, and I have never been wrong.
10, 20, 30%. What you want to look for are 1) small cap 2) down year over year
3) really tanked for no reason from October to December.

After two years watching stocks I already own, this year I want to be
proactive. I plan to do this:
1) Anything with a profit (and favorable tax holding term) that looks extended
I will sell in the next month or two to raise cash.
2) Stocks with a loss I will sell right now but will look for the opportunity
to buy them back cheaper. CAVEAT - who knows tax law - aren't we only allowed
$3,000 in tax losses in a year to offset gains, or will that change with the
new tax bill? I've taken my $3,000 already, unfortunately.

3) And this is the fun part. START IDENTIFYING STOCKS THAT ARE DOWN THIS YEAR.
SET A REASONABLE TARGET PRICE TO BUY AND THEN DISCOUNT THAT PRICE BY 15%. AT
THE END OF DECEMBER (b/t Christmas and New Years) BUY WHATEVER FALLS INTO THAT
RANGE. You'll find some very profitable buys. The key is to raise cash now,
because you won't be able to do it then in small caps.

A few I might suggest to start researching. JC, WHX, HYDEA.
