Date:10/15/1997 8:11:00 PM
From:James Clarke

How about a $9 billion stock that trades at 50% below its value? Before you get
too excited...its an airline. What a crappy business, but everybody knows that.
The crappiness (if that's a word) of the industry is in the price. The industry
is earning much more than it ever has, but it trades at 8 or 9 times earnings
in a market trading at 21 times.

But lets say airlines are fairly valued at that price. And that is highly
debatable. What if the leader in the industry were trading at a 40% discount to
its comparables. That sounds like an opporunity.

Every value investor needs to take a look at AMR, the parent of American
Airlines. It trades at $120 and absolutely blew out estimates today but didn't
move. To keep you reading, I think it is worth at least $170.

Back out its holdings in Sabre, which are quoted on the NYSE. That's about $35
per share of AMR even after its plunge today. (AMR owns 107 million shares.)
Then back out the cash, which is $18 a share. There is another non-core
business worth $5-10 a share. So there's about $60 out of a $120 stock. Now
lets look at the airline.

American Airlines is among the leaders in its industry. It makes over $3
billion (with a B) of EBITDA + lease payments (cash flow) per year. United,
Delta and Continental trade at 5 x EBITDA + payments. So that's $15 billion.
There is 4.7 billion of debt and leases. So we'll back that out to get to
roughly $10 billion for the airline's equity. Divide by 90 million shares and
you get to a $111 per share for the airline. Now we add back the $60 of
non-airline value and you get to $171 a share. The stock trades at $120, blew
out estimates today, leads its industry, and has a great balance sheet.

Look forward to responses.

Jim
