%BOM---------------------
Date:10/15/1997 11:59:00 PM
From:Ron Bower

Stuart,

You are good!! You just shot my analysis of CERB to pieces. It never occured to
me to compare the earnings/revs from prior Qs. I think you were off in the
numbers and it's worse than you stated. The .46 profit last Q came from a .57
tax credit and the actual earnings were a -.11. The company had a tax liability
due to Capital Office profits. When the Capital numbers were put into
'discontinued ops' the tax liability went with it leaving the losses from INEI
= a .57 boost in earnings.

The order backlog reduction you mentioned is significant. If they had revs of
$8M with a $3M reduction in backlog, they only added $5M in new contracts.

Combine the two items you've pointed out and it really reduces the earnings
projections. All that's left is the price at 55% of BV and the cash. Rethinking
position, but will likely look for an opportunity to get out of it without
getting burnt too bad. Thanx loads!

As to the preferred - you must be referring to the B shares. These are
convertible 1:1 to A common. These shares aren't traded on the market and are
held primarily by the Eriksons. Each share has 10X the voting power of an A
share. The 200K+ shares = 2M+ voting rights to the outstanding 1.2M+ A common
rights of 1 vote = 1.2M+. This gives the power in the Eriksons with each owning
1/2 of B and if they disagree, the A shares decide. In the sale of Capital
decision, the Eriksons abstained from voting.

The non-owned interests are the float of INEI. They had on books at share value
before the Capital sale, then changed it to equity basis. I may have done this
to offset some of the capital gains due.

Really appreciate the work you put into this and for the posting. I didn't and
don't know if I would have caught the earnings discrepancy. You've given me a
new thing to look at when I research a stock. This really changed the
situation. I now have the feeling that CERB may sell INEI and dissolve netting
the $16+. One could hold on speculation like this, but not me.

Thanx again,
Ron
