Date:10/22/1997 11:52:00 AM
From:Ron Bower

Paul,

I try to look at sectors I think will do well, then find companies in those
sectors that I think have potential. This is why I looked at agricultural
machinery. I deal with farmers on a daily basis and am certainly no expert, but
I do follow the sector closely.

Farming has changed and it's requiring new equipment. It is highly profitable
and will continue to be for many years to come. I won't go into why, just to
say that farming is now highly profitable BIG business.

The depressed farm economy of the early '80s weeded out the poorly managed
manufacturing companies. There are now four dominant companies: Deere,
Case/IHC, NH, & AG. Deere and Case have the highest recognition in the US, but
NH is gaining. In the world market, NH is equal or even better positioned. AG's
strength is in small equipment rather than the tractors, combines, etc. and
they also are well positioned in the international market. Deere and Case are
being hurt by their construction divisions. CAT is entering the ag market
because of poor construction sales and strong potential of the ag machinery
market.

You make a mistake when you refer to China as 'the' emerging market. They are
currently a major buyer of farm products, not farm equipment. The emerging
markets are Russia, the former Soviet block, and South America followed by
Africa, and Middle East (India). Each will develop as the infrastructure of the
countries develop. (doesn't do any good to grow it if you can't get it to the
market) China is future market.

I have targeted both NH and AG at least 25% above current levels in 6 months
and have added them to diversify portfolio.

For what it's worth,
Ron

