Date:10/22/1997 8:10:00 PM
From:James Clarke

Strong argument. There's the bear case on ag equipment stocks and you presented
it as well as the best Wall Street analyst after what seems to be about 10
minutes of thinking. Thats why we have this message board.

Rebuttal. The ag equipment industry is indeed cyclical, but so is the
construction equipment industry. Caterpillar trades at a 15 multiple while New
Holland and Agco trade at 10-12. Weak argument, I know. I don't totally buy the
"secular growth" argument in agriculture, which is why I would say no to Deere,
but I will present it briefly. Ag equipment is now a global industry. It wasn't
when it was cyclical (Deere was the only pure play public company and it was
almost totally U.S.) It is hard to argue with the thesis that global
agriculture is a growth industry. Populations grow. Countries prosper and want
better food. Production methods have to improve. The difference between what a
U.S. farmer and what a Chinese or Indian farmer can produce on an acre of land
is incredible. There are really only four global competitors in this industry -
Deere, Case, New Holland and Agco. That looks like an oligopoly to me.

Like I said, I don't totally buy it, but at 11x earnings on New Holland and
especially 10x earnings on Agco, you're not going to lose. I'm really thinkng
about buying Agco now. 30 has been a real support level - there are alot of us
institutional investors who will buy the hell out of it at 30. Agco, unlike the
others, is able to grow earnings at 20% for the next couple years. (Don't get
fooled by the last few quarters of New Holland. This is a 10% grower at best
that left itself a free ride for a year when it went public last November). Its
cheap, but its not as cheap as Agco.
